<div id="review_512808961" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/512808961" />
    <a title="Ariele" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16539317-ariele"><img alt="Ariele" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/512808961?book_show_action=true">Jan 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ariele" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ariele" href="/user/show/16539317-ariele">Ariele</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer512808961" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1185711106121651733">At the end, great books give us a feeling of closure, beauty, and redemption. Corbin Addison has triumphed by doing that with his first novel, a thriller about a difficult-to-read subject - human trafficking. <br/><br/>The novel vacillates between the stories of Ahalya and Sita, sisters who are left orphaned and homeless by a tsunami on the coast of India, and Thomas Clark, a lawyer in Washington D.C facing a personal and professional crisis. As Thomas makes fateful decisions to bring meaning to his life,</span>
  <span id="freeText1185711106121651733" style="display:none">At the end, great books give us a feeling of closure, beauty, and redemption. Corbin Addison has triumphed by doing that with his first novel, a thriller about a difficult-to-read subject - human trafficking. <br /><br />The novel vacillates between the stories of Ahalya and Sita, sisters who are left orphaned and homeless by a tsunami on the coast of India, and Thomas Clark, a lawyer in Washington D.C facing a personal and professional crisis. As Thomas makes fateful decisions to bring meaning to his life, he heads off to Mumbai to work for an organization that prosecutes human traffickers. When he learns about Sita and Ahalya, he makes it his personal mission to rescue them.<br /><br />Addison's characters are strong and believable, and his strong writing brings to life the streets of Mumbai and Paris. The second half of the book, as the girls deal with the harsh realities of life in the sex trade and Thomas' search for the girls intensifies, is intense and poetic.<br /><br />I could not put this book down, and recommend it highly. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1185711106121651733" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


