  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_316595444" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/316595444" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3156196-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1264307588p2/3156196.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/316595444?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/3156196-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer316595444" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4024981128230822984">A Walk Across the Sun is one of those amazing books that allow us as privileged, safe Americans to become emotionally involved in issues that do not often personally affect us. One approach is the non-fiction description like Tracy Kidder&apos;s Mountains Beyond Mountains. Though there are a few such good non-fiction books out there (like that one) I think that very well-written fiction does a much better job since it causes us to become invested in the the characters from almost a first-person persp</span>
  <span id="freeText4024981128230822984" style="display:none">A Walk Across the Sun is one of those amazing books that allow us as privileged, safe Americans to become emotionally involved in issues that do not often personally affect us. One approach is the non-fiction description like Tracy Kidder's Mountains Beyond Mountains. Though there are a few such good non-fiction books out there (like that one) I think that very well-written fiction does a much better job since it causes us to become invested in the the characters from almost a first-person perspective. This is one of those great books, and its crisp pace keeps you coming back for more when a less skilled author would let the plot become bogged down in explanations and exhortations.<br /><br />Points of view change through the book in order to tell the story more effectively, but the one that offers us the easiest bridge into the world of human trafficking is Thomas, a complex man in a complicated life situation who nevertheless invites more drama by reaching out to try to save two girls who have no one else to take up their cause. I often find my self exasperated by literary characters who fling themselves into such quixotic situations, but Addison's writing of the character helps me understand why he chooses this path.<br /><br />I'd recommend this book to anyone who enjoys a good read, and hope that it inspires others to take action against the tragedy at its core.<br /><br />I will truly be looking forward to Addison's next novel.<br /><br />I received this book as a First Reads winner. Thank you Goodreads!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4024981128230822984" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


